{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01MgFR97nLy1namdhEd7ABKY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Q99Nboafhj9MbovHfUFjnN","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The core failure would be: the tool counts a renamed file as both a deletion and an addition, double-counting it. This is a parsing and categorization bug. Git's status format uses standard rename indicators (e.g., 'R100' in porcelain format). A mock of the subprocess call to git, returning properly formatted rename output, is sufficient to verify the tool correctly parses and categorizes renames separately without double-counting. The tool's logic is the issue, not git's behavior, so we don't need real git—we need to verify the tool's parsing against a known output format.","test_description":"Mock subprocess.run() to return git status in porcelain v2 format with a rename indicator (e.g., '1 renamed  R100 file.txt newfile.txt'). Run the tool and verify: (1) the report contains exactly one 'renamed' entry for this change, (2) there is no corresponding 'added' or 'deleted' entry for the same file, (3) the report is correctly structured.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure would be: the tool crashes or hangs when encountering binary file markers in git diff output. Git represents binary files with a standard format: 'Binary files a/file.bin and b/file.bin differ'. This is a parsing robustness issue. A mock of git diff output that includes binary file markers is 